.TH QUICKAP 1 "July 2026" "quickap 1.4.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
quickap \- file indexer with content-based duplicate detection
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B quickap
.RI [ command ]
.RI [ flags ]
.RI [ directory ]
.br
.B quickap help
.RI [ command ]
.br
.B quickap version
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B quickap
recursively indexes application, archive, document, image, video, and
music files under a directory \(em plus an \(lqother\(rq category for
every file those six don't claim \(em and prints a per-category
summary: total count, count and size per extension, total size, and
duplicate statistics based on file content (SHA-256).
.PP
The directory to scan defaults to the current one; pass a different one
as the
.B last
argument, after any flags.
Relative
.B \-move
and
.B \-ignore
paths resolve against the scanned directory.
.PP
The bare
.B quickap
command prints a compact overview of every category: one row per
category with file count, size, unique and duplicate counts, and
reclaimable space, plus a reclaimable-space meter when duplicates
exist.
A category command
.RB ( "quickap images" ,
.BR "quickap docs" ,
\&...) prints a detailed report for that category alone \(em a summary
table, a reclaimable-space meter, and a per-extension breakdown with
two-tone bars (unique vs.\& duplicate) \(em and enables the cleanup
flags
.B \-move
and
.BR \-delete .
.PP
Duplicates are
.B byte-identical
files, regardless of filename or extension: the same bytes saved as
.I movie.mp4
and
.I movie-copy.mkv
are caught, while similar-looking but re-encoded or resized files are
not flagged.
Within each group of identical files, the lexically first path counts
as the original; the rest are duplicates.
.SH COMMANDS
.TP
.I (none)
Index all categories and print the compact overview.
.TP
.B apps
Index applications only (aliases:
.BR app ,
.BR applications ).
.TP
.B archives
Index archives only (alias:
.BR archive ).
.TP
.B docs
Index documents only (alias:
.BR documents ).
.TP
.B images
Index images only.
.TP
.B videos
Index videos only (alias:
.BR video ).
.TP
.B music
Index music only.
.TP
.B other
Index files no other category claims (alias:
.BR others ).
.TP
.BR help " [" \fIcommand\fR ]
Show the built-in help, or help for one command.
.TP
.B version
Print the version and exit.
.SH OPTIONS
Flags operate on the current command's category (or all categories for
the bare command).
Flags must come
.B before
the trailing directory argument.
.TP
.BR \-list\-duplicates ", " \-ld
List each duplicate group with file paths.
The kept original is marked with a check mark, duplicate copies with a
cross.
.TP
.BR \-list\-unique ", " \-lu
List every unique file with its size \(em exactly what the report's
\(lqunique\(rq column counts: every file that is not a duplicate copy,
so a group's kept original is included.
.TP
.BR \-list\-large ", " \-ll
List the 50 largest files with their sizes, largest first.
.TP
.BI \-ignore " DIR"
Skip a directory while scanning.
A bare name
.RI ( node_modules )
skips every directory with that name anywhere in the tree; a path
containing a separator
.RI ( files/cache )
skips only that path relative to the scanned directory.
Repeat the flag or comma-separate values for multiple directories:
.BR "\-ignore tunes,media \-ignore dist" .
.TP
.B \-hidden
Include hidden directories
.RI ( .foo/ )
in the scan.
They are skipped by default.
.TP
.B \-no\-cache
Disable the hash cache for this run \(em no reads from or writes to
it.
.TP
.B \-verify
Re-hash every duplicate candidate, ignoring cached hashes.
The cache is still updated with the fresh results.
Use this if you suspect a file changed without its size or
modification time changing.
.TP
.B \-clear\-cache
Delete the hash cache entirely and exit.
The next scan re-hashes from scratch.
.TP
.B \-spacious
Add vertical space between table rows for easier reading.
The default is compact.
.TP
.BR \-verbose ", " \-vv
Show scan details below the report: timing, hash-cache statistics
(e.g.\& \(lq12 hashed, 240 from cache\(rq), and hints.
Off by default.
Unreadable entries are always reported, even without this flag.
.TP
.B \-version
Print the version and exit.
.TP
.B \-help
Show help for the current command.
.PP
The cleanup flags act on one category at a time, so they require a
category command
.RB "(e.g.\& " "quickap images \-delete" ");"
the bare command indexes and reports only.
.TP
.BI \-move " DIR"
Move each duplicate group \(em
.B original and copies
\(em into
.IB DIR /\fIcategory\fP/group-NNN/
for manual side-by-side sorting.
.I DIR
is created if needed and resolved relative to the scanned directory.
Original filenames are kept; name collisions within a group get a
numeric suffix
.RI ( a.jpg ,
.IR a-2.jpg ),
detected case-insensitively so nothing is overwritten on
case-insensitive filesystems (macOS APFS, Windows).
Moves fall back to copy-plus-delete across filesystems.
Cannot be combined with
.BR \-delete .
.TP
.B \-delete
.B Permanently delete
duplicate files, keeping each group's original (the lexically first
path).
There is no undo.
Run
.B \-list\-duplicates
first to review exactly which file each group keeps, or use
.B \-move
to sort manually instead.
Cannot be combined with
.BR \-move .
.SH CATEGORIES
Extensions are matched case-insensitively.
.TP
.B apps
\&.apk .appimage .deb .dmg .exe .msi .pkg .rpm
.TP
.B archives
\&.7z .7zip .bz2 .gz .iso .rar .tar .tbz .tgz .xz .zip .zst
.TP
.B documents
\&.csv .doc .docx .epub .md .odp .ods .odt .pdf .ppt .pptx .rtf .txt
\&.xls .xlsx
.TP
.B images
\&.avif .bmp .gif .heic .heif .ico .jpeg .jpg .png .svg .tif .tiff
\&.webp
.TP
.B videos
\&.3gp .avi .flv .m4v .mkv .mov .mp4 .mpeg .mpg .ogv .webm .wmv
.TP
.B music
\&.aac .aif .aiff .flac .m4a .mid .midi .mp3 .ogg .opus .wav .wma
.TP
.B other files
Everything the categories above don't claim, including files with no
extension (shown as
.B (none)
in the per-extension report).
The seven categories together always account for every file in the
scan, hidden and ignored directories aside.
.SH DUPLICATE DETECTION
Files are grouped by byte size first; only same-size candidates are
hashed (SHA-256, in parallel across CPU cores), so unique-sized files
are never read and scans stay fast on large trees.
Duplicates are detected within each category independently.
.PP
The \(lqduplicates\(rq count is the number of redundant copies: a
group of three identical files counts as one original plus two
duplicates.
Files that cannot be read count as unique.
.SS The hash cache
Computed hashes are cached between runs.
A cached hash is reused when the file's size and modification time are
unchanged, so repeat scans only read new or modified files.
All scans share a single cache keyed by absolute file path, so hashing
a parent directory also warms the cache for later scans of its
subdirectories.
Nothing is ever written into the scanned directories themselves.
.PP
Housekeeping is automatic: entries for files deleted under the scanned
directory are pruned on each run (entries from other trees are left
alone), and a missing or corrupt cache file just means the next run
re-hashes everything.
Deleting the cache directory is always safe and is equivalent to a
one-time
.B \-no\-cache
run.
.SH FILES
.TP
.I ~/.cache/quickap/hashes.json
The hash cache on Linux and the BSDs (or
.IR $XDG_CACHE_HOME/quickap/hashes.json
if set).
On macOS:
.IR ~/Library/Caches/quickap/ ;
on Windows:
.IR %LocalAppData%\equickap\e .
A JSON map of path to size, mtime, and SHA-256 for every file that has
been content-hashed.
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B NO_COLOR
When set (to any non-empty value), disables all color and styling.
Color is also disabled automatically when standard output is not a
terminal (e.g.\& when piped).
.TP
.B XDG_CACHE_HOME
Overrides the base directory for the hash cache on Linux and the BSDs.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Success.
.TP
.B 1
Error: unknown command, nonexistent or invalid scan directory, more
than one directory argument,
.B \-delete
combined with
.BR \-move ,
or a failure while moving duplicate groups.
.PP
Unreadable files and directories inside the scan are skipped and
counted in the report footer, never fatal.
.SH EXAMPLES
Overview of the current directory, then drill into one category:
.PP
.nf
.RS
quickap
quickap images
quickap images \-verbose ~/Pictures
.RE
.fi
.PP
Clean up a photo library carefully \(em review, then move groups out
for side-by-side sorting:
.PP
.nf
.RS
quickap images \-list\-duplicates
quickap images \-move ../photo\-dupes
.RE
.fi
.PP
Clean up decisively \(em one last look, then delete duplicates keeping
each group's original:
.PP
.nf
.RS
quickap videos \-ld
quickap videos \-delete
.RE
.fi
.PP
Scope the scan \(em skip build output by name, a specific folder by
path, or include hidden directories:
.PP
.nf
.RS
quickap \-ignore node_modules,dist
quickap docs \-ignore files/archive
quickap images \-hidden \-ignore .git
.RE
.fi
.PP
Find what is eating disk space in a Downloads folder:
.PP
.nf
.RS
quickap \-list\-large ~/Downloads
quickap archives \-list\-duplicates ~/Downloads
.RE
.fi
.PP
Force a fresh look at the data, bypassing or refreshing the cache:
.PP
.nf
.RS
quickap \-verify
quickap \-no\-cache \-vv
.RE
.fi
.SH NOTES
The summary report always reflects the state
.B before
.BR \-move / \-delete
ran.
.PP
A
.B \-move
target inside the scanned directory will be re-indexed on the next
run; use a target outside it (e.g.\&
.IR ../dupes )
to avoid that.
.PP
Symbolic links and other non-regular files (sockets, FIFOs, devices)
are ignored \(em never followed, indexed, or hashed \(em so a link and
its target are never flagged as duplicates of each other.
A symlinked scan directory itself is resolved to its target before
scanning.
